# banned-vocab.patterns — §10 Specificity / Honesty banned vocabulary.
# One extended-regex (grep -iE) per line. `#` lines and blanks ignored.
# Scanned against git commit messages (PreToolUse:Bash) and, later, assistant
# prose (Stop transcript scan). A hit = an unquantified value claim → the spec
# requires an absolute number or baseline-anchored ratio instead.
# Keep patterns anchored to whole words to avoid substring false positives.

# ── English ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
\bshould work\b
\brobust(ly|ness)?\b
\bsignificantly\b
\bcomprehensive(ly)?\b
\bseamless(ly)?\b
\bblazing(ly)? fast\b
\b[0-9]+x faster\b
\bmuch (faster|better|cleaner)\b
\bgreatly impro(ve|ved|ves)\b
\bproduction[- ]ready\b

# ── 中文 ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
显著提升
显著改善
应该可以
基本可用
已完善
大幅提升
完美(解决|支持|兼容)

# ── §6 bugfix-anchor banned phrasings (missing-evidence tokens) ────────────
# spec/AGENTS.md §6 lists these as "= missing evidence"; hard-rules §6-bugfix-anchor
# declares this pattern set as its enforcement surface. Bypass any non-evaluative
# use with [allow-vocab]. (The English "it runs" is deliberately NOT a blocking
# pattern here — a bare regex false-blocks legitimate commit text like "when it runs
# out of memory"; it stays covered by self-enforced Iron Law #2 + the Stop advisory.)
看上去\s*ok
跑过了
没问题了
